## Playing a Spellcaster

### Managing Your Momentum Economy

Spellcasters move through predictable phases in combat:

**Building Phase (Rounds 1-2)**
Cast Spark repeatedly in Aggressive stance. Each hit generates +2 Momentum (Aggressive stance bonus +1, spell hit +1). You're building toward +3 or +4 Momentum while contributing damage.

Maintain Mage Armor for defense. It costs nothing after initial cast and significantly improves your survivability.

**Power Phase (Rounds 3-4)**
Cast your advanced spells (typically -1 Momentum). If they deal damage and you're in Aggressive stance, you recover +1 Momentum immediately.

Use expert spells (-2 Momentum typically) for decisive moments. These should feel like big moves, not routine actions.

**Recovery Phase (If Needed)**
Return to cantrips to rebuild Momentum if the fight continues. Switch to Defensive stance if you're taking attention.

The cycle repeats. Good spellcasters know when to conserve and when to unload.

### Choosing Your Casting Attribute

Don't always use your highest attribute. Consider:

**Use Mind When:**
- You need precision (avoiding allies in area effects)
- Efficiency matters (maximize healing per Momentum)
- You want technical control over raw power

**Use Awareness When:**
- You need maximum damage
- You're exploiting weaknesses or vulnerabilities
- Raw power trumps precision

**Use Will When:**
- You're at negative Momentum but must cast anyway
- You need persistence or duration
- Determination matters more than finesse

**Use Presence When:**
- Social or emotional effects enhance the spell
- You want to affect minds and morale
- Force of personality achieves what technique can't

All four approaches work. Choosing situationally creates more interesting magic than always defaulting to your best attribute.

