## Game Master Guidance

### Supporting Flexible Casting

When a player casts a spell, ask: "How are you casting this?" Encourage them to choose their attribute consciously, not reflexively.

Describe how different attribute approaches manifest. Mind-cast Fireball creates a precisely controlled explosion. Awareness-cast Fireball senses vulnerabilities and burns hotter. Will-cast Fireball erupts through pure determination. Presence-cast Fireball terrifies as much as it burns.

Don't penalize players for suboptimal choices. If someone wants to cast through Presence instead of their higher Mind, support it. Mechanical variety creates narrative richness.

### Common Oversights

**Armor Penalties:** Don't forget that armor reduces Sorcery for casting. Light armor -1, medium armor -1, heavy armor -4.

**Attribute Flexibility:** Avoid treating all spells as Mind-based. That's how other games work—this system is deliberately different.

**Will's Negative Momentum Casting:** This is powerful and intentional. Will casters sacrifice other benefits to cast when desperate.

**Cantrip Economy:** Players sometimes undervalue cantrips. Remind them that Spark generates Momentum in combat.

### Balancing the Four Traditions

All four attribute approaches should feel viable. Design encounters that reward different traditions:

- Tight quarters favor Mind (precision with allies nearby)
- Dangerous enemies favor Awareness (maximize damage quickly)
- Resource-depleted scenarios favor Will (cast at negative Momentum)
- Social conflicts favor Presence (affect minds and morale)

When all four traditions have moments to shine, magic feels truly flexible.

